{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538560"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:29:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:29:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16217"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16217","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16217"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.12,0.02,0.03,0.81]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8908"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106123"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8908","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8908"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16217"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88598"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1353"},{"type":"tags","id":"4166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4168"},{"type":"tags","id":"4192"},{"type":"tags","id":"4193"},{"type":"tags","id":"4194"},{"type":"tags","id":"4195"},{"type":"tags","id":"4540"},{"type":"tags","id":"10948"},{"type":"tags","id":"10950"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38928"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38953"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106123"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the gynaecology clinic with her partner with a 14-month history of inability to conceive. She has irregular menstrual cycles occurring every two to three months. She has a medical history of polycystic ovarian syndrome diagnosed three years ago. She does not take any regular medications. Her BMI is 27 kg/m2. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is evidence of hirsutism on her face and abdomen. Her partner\u0027s semen analysis is normal. Blood tests reveal: follicle stimulating hormone 6 IU/L (3-8), luteinizing hormone 12 IU/L (2-8), testosterone 2.8 nmol/L (0.5-2.0), prolactin 450 mIU/L (100-500), and day 21 progesterone 2 nmol/L (\u003E30). Pelvic Ultrasound reveals polycystic ovaries bilaterally though is otherwise normal. A hysterosalpingogram shows patent fallopian tubes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Laparoscopy","In vitro fertilisation","Intracytoplasmic sperm injection","Intrauterine insemination","Ovulation induction with clomiphene citrate or letrozole"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with infertility in the context of polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS), confirmed by irregular cycles, hyperandrogenism (elevated testosterone and hirsutism), elevated luteinizing hormone to follicle stimulating hormone ratio, and low day 21 progesterone indicating anovulation. With patent fallopian tubes and normal semen analysis, anovulation is likely the primary cause of infertility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvulation induction with clomiphene citrate or letrozole\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line treatment. Both medications work by increasing follicle stimulating hormone secretion, leading to follicular development and ovulation. Clomiphene is a selective oestrogen receptor modulator, while letrozole is an aromatase inhibitor. The success rate for ovulation is approximately 80% with a pregnancy rate of 40% after six cycles. Recent studies suggest letrozole may have better efficacy in women with PCOS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there was suspicion of endometriosis or tubal disease. However, with patent fallopian tubes on hysterosalpingogram and no symptoms suggestive of endometriosis, laparoscopy is not warranted as the first step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIn vitro fertilisation\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered only after failure of less invasive treatments, particularly given the patient\u0027s young age and the absence of other fertility factors. It would be premature to proceed directly to IVF without first attempting ovulation induction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntracytoplasmic sperm injection\u003C/strong\u003E is specifically indicated for male factor infertility. With normal semen analysis, this advanced reproductive technique is not required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntrauterine insemination\u003C/strong\u003E may be considered in combination with ovulation induction if there is no pregnancy after several cycles of ovulation induction alone. However, it is not the most appropriate first step given that anovulation is the primary issue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditionally, lifestyle modifications, particularly weight loss given her elevated BMI, should be recommended alongside any fertility treatment as this can improve both spontaneous and assisted conception rates.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Clomiphene citrate or letrozole are first-line therapy options for ovulation induction in women with PCOS who are trying to conceive.","Weight loss should be recommended for women with PCOS who have a BMI \u003E25 kg/m2 before starting fertility treatment.","Anovulation is the primary cause of infertility in PCOS and can be diagnosed with low day 21 progesterone levels."],"references":["Vyrides AA, El Mahdi E, Giannakou K. Ovulation induction techniques in women with polycystic ovary syndrome. Front Med (Lausanne). 2022 Aug 12;9:982230. doi: 10.3389/fmed.2022.982230. PMID: 36035398; PMCID: PMC9411864."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88598"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16217"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88598"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-16T07:24:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-16T07:26:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8908"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106123"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description"